White Wine Analysis

Abstract

This analysis shall provide exploaratory data analysis for the white wine data set. It includes different 4898 observation for white wine samples. a set of different 11 variables about the white wine has been recorded for each sample in addition to wine quality, there is one field for the record indexing. The inputs include objective tests (e.g.PH values) and the output is based on sensory data (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts). Each expert graded the wine quality between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Input variables (based on physicochemical tests): 1 - fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3) 2 - volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3) 3 - citric acid (g / dm^3) 4 - residual sugar (g / dm^3) 5 - chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3 6 - free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3) 7 - total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3) 8 - density (g / cm^3) 9 - pH 10 - sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3) 11 - alcohol (% by volume)

Output variable (based on sensory data): 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

What is the structure of your dataset?

My dataset has 4898 observation for white wine samples with 12 different variables

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The wine quality is the main features along with different 11 attributes

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest? I will explore the 11 attributes to check if they have relation with the wine quality

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes, I created one factor transformation for the quality

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

This dataset appears to be relatively simple not high percentage or outliers or missing values. The quality is a discrete value and also based on human measurement so may have some bias so would prefer dealing with it a categorical value so I made a copy of it as factor. 3 fields are having clear outliers residual.sugar, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide

Some variables appear to have positive correlation with each other like residual.sugar with density while other appear to have negative correlation like density with total.sulfur.dioxide. With respect to quality (last line plots) nothing appear to have strong relation. In coming section will further explore detailed correlation between variables.

ggcorr(ww,digits=2,label = TRUE,label_size=3)
## Warning in ggcorr(ww, digits = 2, label = TRUE, label_size = 3): data in
## column(s) 'quality_index' are not numeric and were ignored

As shown based on correlation factor, we can see 6 different ranges: -0.3>0, 0>0.3: no correlation or poor correlation relation -0.7>-0.3, 0.3>0.7: medium correlation relation -1 >-0.7, 0.7 >1: strong correlation relation the negative sign refer to inverse relation while the positive refer to positive relation

We can then state the positive strong relations: residual.sugar and desnsity:0.8 free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide:0.7

We can then state the negative strong relations: density and alcohol:-0.8

Medium relation example: residual.sugar and total.sulfur.dioxide:0.4 residual.sugar and alcohol:-0.5

for the quality we have medium positive relation with alcohol and medium negative relation with density

  geom_boxplot(fill=I('orange'),color='black',shape=19)

From the box plot it appears the median for the alcohol increase with quality except for quality 3 and 4 however as the number of samples is small so potential bias may exist so I will narrow down the quality from 10 category into 3 as it is easy for drinks to have opinion bad,normal,good so will create quality.bucket to group the samples into 3 different categories

#Narrow the quality to 3 categories to minimize the samples distribution variation

ww$quality.bucket <- cut(ww$quality,labels = c('Low','Medium','High'),
                             c(1,5.9,6.1,10))
table(ww$quality.bucket)
## 
##    Low Medium   High 
##   1640   2198   1060

Now the distribution of samples into 3 categories is more balanced and would be used in the coming analysis.

#plotting relation between quality bucket and alcohol
ggplot(aes(x=quality.bucket,y=alcohol),data=ww)+
  geom_boxplot(fill=I('orange'),color='black',shape=19)

Now appear more relationship, so on average the increase of alcohol increase the wine quality

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

As per the correlation matrix, we can see 6 different ranges: -0.3>0, 0>0.3: no correlation or poor correlation relation -0.7>-0.3, 0.3>0.7: medium correlation relation -1 >-0.7, 0.7 >1: strong correlation relation the negative sign refer to inverse relation while the positive refer to positive relation

We can then state the positive strong relations: residual.sugar and desnsity:0.8 free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide:0.7

We can then state the negative strong relations: density and alcohol:-0.8

Medium relation example: residual.sugar and total.sulfur.dioxide:0.4 residual.sugar and alcohol:-0.5

for the quality we have medium positive relation with alcohol and medium negative relation with density

My concern is that there are 2 other factors: the crapes type (manufature time, source country) as well as the experts information (age group, sex, nationality) as this would bias their judgement as well.
